From 716899ef1ec771e4334010bd0bd907d37dc07de0 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Vicegerent Maintainers <noreply@example.com>
Date: Sat, 11 Jul 2026 17:49:52 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] llm: mask promptGuard text in place, never round-trip through
 get_messages/set_messages

apply_regex()/apply_regex_response() previously scanned for a mask match by
flattening every message via get_messages() and, on any match, wrote the
full message list back via set_messages(). Both get_messages() and
set_messages() round-trip through SimpleChatCompletionMessage { role,
content: Strng }, which has no representation for anything but plain text.
A message whose content is entirely non-text blocks -- most commonly a
tool_result-only user turn, the normal shape of every message immediately
following a tool call -- flattens to an empty string on the way in, and
set_messages() writes that empty string back as the message's entire
content on the way out. Anthropic's API then rejects the request with
'messages.N: user messages must have non-empty content'.

Reject detection is unaffected by this bug (it returns before ever calling
set_messages()), so it keeps using get_messages() unchanged.

Fix: add RequestType::mask_text_content()/ResponseType::mask_text_content(),
a new trait method that walks each format's own content representation and
masks only genuine text spans (ContentBlock::Text, ContentPart::Text, etc),
leaving every other content type -- tool_use, tool_result, images, and any
JSON shape wrapped in ContentPart::Unknown -- completely untouched. Wire
apply_regex()/apply_regex_response() to call this for Action::Mask instead
of the lossy get_messages()/set_messages() round-trip.

Implemented for every RequestType/ResponseType this platform routes
promptGuard-masking traffic through:
- Anthropic Messages format (messages.rs) -- the anthropic backend
- OpenAI Completions format (completions.rs) -- the openai/haiku-oai backends
- OpenAI Responses format (responses.rs) -- the openai backend's /v1/responses
  route; walks the raw JSON per-item so any item shape without a typed model
  (function_call, function_call_output, reasoning, etc.) passes through
  unmodified
- TextRequest (policy/mod.rs) -- the realtime WebSocket adapter, trivially
  lossless since it wraps a single plain string with no structure to lose

Formats with no dedicated implementation fall back to the trait's default
(no-op, reports unchanged), so they are simply never masked rather than
risking corruption -- never a regression from 'masked' to 'corrupted'.

Adds regression tests reproducing the exact failure (a tool_result-only
message alongside a message that matches a mask pattern) at both the
messages.rs unit level and the Policy::apply_regex dispatch level, plus a
companion test confirming Reject continues to work and never mutates.
